EDA AND XGBOOST FOR EQUIPMENT FAILURE PREDICTION Hanoi, 16/09/2024 Brief explanations for analysis and models for the demo of Equipment Failure Prediction. Part 1: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) For possessing overall understanding of data, we will see basic information on full data, and following EDA will be carried out on training set cause deep dive EDA for the purpose of predicting should be carried out on training set. We do more EDA (above the request) to see the insight. I have divided set into train and test set from such phase. Details I have included in code and concise comment Part 2: XGBoost Model From EDA, we do feature engineer. I build a pipeline for training data. It is found that: precision, recall, f1-score (for label_1) is 0, because in training set, we only have 15 records of label_1 (and in test set we also have only 4 records of label_1). So,model may not learn the pattern to exact predict 4 records of label_1 in test set. Cause we have only 190 records for all training and testing. I have tried scale_pos_weight between negative and positive class to allow the model to compensate for imbalanced data. Scale_pos_weight is assigning more weight to the minority class, making the model more sensitive to misclassifications of the minority class. Also, I tried hyperparameter tuning by randomized search approach for: nestimators ,max_depth ,learning_rate , subsample, colsample_bytree, gamma ,min_child_weight, however, it still does not work well for better predictions. In reality, wish we can have more data (both positive and negative labels) to learn and test more. Im so sorry but cause we dont have many data to train and to put more data involved in imbalance dataset, if we have more data available I will put more positive data into training to enhance the predicting powers. Hope you can sympathize for that <3.

2.2 Training pipeline

In[164]:
# pipeline for training 
# cause it is imbalanced data, so we calculate scale_pos_weight between negative and positive class 
# to help have parameter allows the model to compensate for this by assigning more weight to the minority class, 
# making the model more sensitive to misclassifications of the minority class.


neg_class = (y_train == 0).sum()
pos_class = (y_train == 1).sum()

scale_pos_weight = neg_class / pos_class

# filter numerical and categorical columns 
numerical_columns_selector = selector(dtype_exclude=object)
numerical_columns = numerical_columns_selector(train_set_filter)


categorical_columns_selector = selector(dtype_include=object)
categorical_columns = categorical_columns_selector(train_set_filter)

# transform for each type
numeric_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')),   # Fill missing numerical values with the mean
    ('scaler', StandardScaler())                  # Normalize numerical data
])

categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')),  # Fill missing categorical values with the most frequent value
    ('encoder', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'))    # One-hot encode the categorical features
])

# Combine the transformations for numeric and categorical data
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(transformers=[
    ('num', numeric_transformer, numerical_columns),
    ('cat', categorical_transformer, categorical_columns)
])

xgb = XGBClassifier(use_label_encoder=False, eval_metric='logloss')


# Create the full pipeline with preprocessor and classifier
pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
    ('classifier', XGBClassifier(use_label_encoder=False, eval_metric='logloss',scale_pos_weight=scale_pos_weight))
])

# Train the model
pipeline.fit(train_set_filter, y_train)

Hyperparameter tuning

In[171]:
pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
    ('classifier', XGBClassifier(use_label_encoder=False, eval_metric='logloss',scale_pos_weight=scale_pos_weight))
])

# hyperparam to tune

param_grid = {
    'classifier__n_estimators': [100, 200, 500],
    'classifier__max_depth': [3, 5, 7, 10],
    'classifier__learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.2],
    'classifier__subsample': [0.6, 0.8, 1.0],
    'classifier__colsample_bytree': [0.6, 0.8, 1.0],
    'classifier__gamma': [0, 0.1, 0.3, 0.5],
    'classifier__min_child_weight': [1, 3, 5],
    'classifier__scale_pos_weight': [1, 5, scale_pos_weight, scale_pos_weight+5]  # Adjust based on class imbalance
}

#  Define RandomizedSearchCV
random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(
    estimator=pipeline,
    param_distributions=param_grid,
    n_iter=50,  # Number of hyperparameter combinations to try
    scoring='f1',  # Metric to optimize (e.g., f1, accuracy, etc.)
    cv=3,  # 3-fold cross-validation
    verbose=2,
    random_state=42,
    n_jobs=-1  # Use all available cores
)

#  Fit RandomizedSearchCV on training data
random_search.fit(train_set_filter, y_train)

#  Print the best hyperparameters
print("Best Hyperparameters:", random_search.best_params_)

# Predict using the best estimator
y_pred = random_search.best_estimator_.predict(test_set_filter)

#  Evaluate the model
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
